ibly a metonymic occupational name for someone who looked after bullocks."],"variants":[{"name":"Wolak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Ludwik, Andrzej, Casimir, Genowefa, Janusz, Jaroslaw, Kazimierz, Krzysztof, Piotr, Teofil.","Polish: patronymic from a short form of a personal name, such as <i>Wolimir</i>, based on the Slavic element <i>vol</i> ‘to want’ (from Old Slavic <i>voliti</i>, Polish <i>woleć</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Woley was born about 1285, in Hollingworth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Rafe de Woley, was 36 and his mother, Mrs. Rafe de Woley, was 27. He married Sebilla De Woley in 1308, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1345, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"Abt 1285–1345":"umbes 1285–1345","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1276–1333":"1276–1333","1309–1369":"1309–1369","1250–1325":"1250–1325","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","about 1309":"umbes 1309","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1276":"1276","1309":"1309","1308":"1308","Woley, Hollingsworth, Che